Abstract = {{Field experiment was conducted from 1992 to 2003 at Zonal Agricultural
   Research Station, V. C. Farm, Mandya, Karnataka to study the beneficial
   effect of pulses on soil fertility and sustainability of rice yield in
   paddy-pulses cropping system in Cauvery command area. The mean 10 years'
   research results revealed that growing pulses after or before rice in
   rice-pulses sequence recorded maximum grain yield (5375 to 5550 kg/ha)
   as compared to rice-rice cropping system (5160 kg/ha). Improvement in
   organic carbon (0.54-0.56\%), CEC (10.10 to 10.50 cmol/kg), porosity
   (29.80 to 35.30\%) and maximum water holding capacity (28.90 to
   30.90\%), and drastic reduction in bulk density (1.35 g/cc) was observed
   with rice-pulses cropping system as compared to rice-rice cropping
   system (0.32\%, 9.60 cmol/kg, 26.50\%, 21.20\% and 1.67 g/cc,
   respectively). Available soil nutrientstatus (kg/ha)was rice-pulses
   cropping system (288 N, 65 P(2)O(5), 134 K(2)O 26.70 S and 0.80 Zn) as
   compared to rice-rice sequence (118, 53, 73, 10.10 and 0.16 kg/ha,
   respectively). Water use efficiency was maximum with rice-pulses
   cropping system (55 kg/ha-cm) as compared to rice-rice system (24
   kg/ha-cm) and maximum benefit : cost ratio was obtained with rice-Avare
   cropping system (Rs. 3.04) as compared to rice-rice system (Rs. 2.29).}},
